1. Overview ¶

This project is based on a data challenge from the Michigan Data Science Team (MDST).

The Michigan Data Science Team (MDST) and the Michigan Student Symposium for Interdisciplinary Statistical Sciences (MSSISS) have partnered with the City of Detroit to help solving one of the most pressing problems facing Detroit: blight. Blight violations are issued by the city to individuals who allow their properties to remain in a deteriorated condition. Every year, the city of Detroit issues millions of dollars in fines to residents and every year, many of these fines remain unpaid. Enforcing unpaid blight fines is a costly and tedious process, so the city in interested in insights that may help to understand how to increase blight ticket compliance.

Therefore, it would be useful to understand when and why a resident might fail to comply with a blight ticket. This is where predictive modeling comes in. The task in the Prediction Competition part of the challenge is to predict whether a given blight ticket will be paid on time.

The data for this project has been provided through the Detroit Open Data Portal.

In particular the data that is contained in the kaggle competition has been used as input data in here.

Before fitting any prediction model, the data is analyzed, prepared and cleansed.

Different prediction models are created and fit to the data. The evaluation metric used to compare the different models is the Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC).

A prediction is done with the selected model by using a separate dataset. The prediction is given as the probability that the corresponding blight ticket will be paid on time (that is, at latest within one month of the hearing date). For every entry in the dataset, the result file contains two columns: ticket_id and compliance (a scalar from 0 to 1 inclusive giving the above mentioned probability).

def df_basic_data(dfname):
    # This function prints basic information about a given dataframe.
    # The function needs as input parameters the dataframe name.

    import pandas as pd

    # Fetching the dataframe name
    name = [x for x in globals() if globals()[x] is dfname][0]
    print("Dataframe name:", name, "\n")
    print("Dataframe length:", len(dfname), "\n")
    print("Number of columns:", len(dfname.columns), "\n")
    # Columns data types
    data_types = dfname.dtypes
    # Distint values
    distint_values = dfname.apply(pd.Series.nunique)
    # Amount of null values
    null_values = dfname.isnull().sum()
    print("Dataframe's columns names, column data types, amount of distint "
          "(non null) values\n"
          "and amount of null values for each column:")
    df_index = ['Data_Type',
                'Amount_of_Distint_Values',
                'Amount_of_Null_Values']
    col_types_dist_null = pd.DataFrame([data_types,
                                        distint_values,
                                        null_values],
                                       index=df_index)
    return col_types_dist_null.transpose()

def missing_values(dfname,
                   figsize_w=12, figsize_h=8,
                   ref_font_size=12,
                   title="Missing Values in the Columns of the Dataframe",
                   title_offset=20):
    """
    This function plots a heatmap to visualize the amount of missing values
    in the columns of a pandas dataframe and customizes
    the way the chart looks by using the value of the provided parameters.

    Keyword arguments:
    dfname          -- The name of the dataframe (mandatory)
    figsize_w       -- The width of the plot area
    figsize_w       -- The height of the plot area
    ref_font_size   -- The reference font size
    title           -- A string containing the title of the chart
    title_offset    -- The distance between the title and the top of the chart
    """

    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Creating a new figure
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))
    # Defining the used style
    color_style = sns.color_palette(palette='deep')

    # Adding a title (with some distance to the top of the plot)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=ref_font_size*1.33, pad=title_offset)

    # Plotting a heatmap (with no y axis tick labels and no color bar legend)
    hm = sns.heatmap(dfname.isnull(),
                     yticklabels=False,
                     cbar=False,
                     cmap=color_style)

    # Adding labeles on the x axis
    plt.xlabel("Column names", fontsize=ref_font_size)
    # Setting x axis tick label rotation
    hm.set_xticklabels(hm.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.show()

def cat_perc_split(dfname, columnname, posneg, printout=False):

    '''
    This function takes a categorical variable (columnname) of a dataframe
    (dfname) and creates two series with length equal to the amount of unique
    category values.
    Then for each category value it calculates the percentage of entries
    for each of the two values of a second dataframe column (posneg),
    which contains a binary categorical variable (positive / negative).
    The function prints the result and returns two series containing
    the percentage value for each category,
    separately for the positive and the negative cases
    (the positive case is given first).

    Keyword arguments:
    dfname          -- The name of the dataframe (mandatory)
    columnname      -- A string containing the name of the categorical column
                       (mandatory)
    posneg          -- A string containing the name of the binary
                       categorical column (mandatory)
    printout        -- A boolean variable that controls if to print info (default False)                   
    '''

    # Finding the amount of unique categories in the series
    cat_number = dfname[columnname].nunique()
    # Creating a Series to contain the percentages of positove cases
    # for each category
    pos = pd.Series(index=dfname[columnname].unique().sort_values())
    # Creating a Series to contain the percentages of negative cases
    # for each category
    neg = pd.Series(index=dfname[columnname].unique().sort_values())

    # Iterating through the unique values of the variable columnname
    for name, i in zip(dfname[columnname].unique().sort_values(),
                       list(range(cat_number))):
        # Finding the percentage of positive and negavive values
        # for each category
        split = dfname[dfname[columnname] == name][posneg]\
                .value_counts(normalize=True)*100  # series
        # Adding percentages of negative cases to the Series created above
        neg.at[i] = split[0]
        # Adding percentages of positive cases to the Series created above
        pos.at[i] = 100 - split[0]
        if printout:
            print("Category:", name, "\n",
                  "Negative cases in percentage:", split[0], "\n",
                  "Positive cases in percentage:", 100 - split[0], "\n")

    return pos, neg

def cust_scatter_matrix(dfname, columns,
                        figsize=15, font_size=15,
                        title=None, title_offset=0.945):
    """
    This function plots a scatter matrix for the provided data and customizes
    the way the chart looks by using the value of the provided parameters.

    Keyword arguments:
    dfname          -- The name of a pandas dataframe (mandatory)
    columns         -- A list of column names (mandatory)
    figsize         -- The reference figure size (default = 15)
    font_size       -- The reference font size (default = 15)
    title           -- A string containing the title of the chart
                       (default: None)
    title_offset    -- The offset of the title
    """

    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

    # Creating a scatter matrix
    sm = pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(dfname.loc[:, columns],
                                    figsize=[figsize, figsize])

    # Adding a title
    plt.suptitle(title,
                 fontsize=1.7*font_size,
                 y=title_offset)

    # Formatting the axes' labels and ticks
    for ax in sm.ravel():
        ax.set_xlabel(ax.get_xlabel(), fontsize=1.1*font_size,
                      rotation=0, labelpad=0.66*font_size)
        ax.set_ylabel(ax.get_ylabel(), fontsize=1.1*font_size,
                      rotation=90, labelpad=0.66*font_size)
        ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(labelsize=0.95*font_size, pad=0.33*font_size)
        ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(labelsize=0.95*font_size, pad=0.33*font_size)

def cust_pairplot(df, target,
                  s=2,
                  font_size=12,
                  col_numb1=1,
                  col_numb2=2,
                  title=None, title_offset=1):
    """
    This function plots a pair plot for the provided data and customizes
    the way the chart looks by using the value of the provided parameters.

    Keyword arguments:
    df              -- A pandas dataframe (mandatory)
    target          -- A string containing the name of the column containing
                       the target value (mandatory)
    s               -- It controls the size of the figure
    col_numb1,
    col_numb2       -- The colors to be used in the heatmap
    font_size       -- The reference font size (default = 12)
    title           -- A string containing the title of the chart
                       (default: None)
    title_offset    -- The offset of the title
    """

    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Creating a pair plot
    pp = sns.pairplot(df, hue=target,
                      diag_kind='hist',
                      height=s,
                      palette=[sns.color_palette(palette='deep')[col_numb1],
                               sns.color_palette(palette='deep')[col_numb2]])

    # Adding a title
    pp.fig.suptitle(title,
                    fontsize=1.5*font_size,
                    y=title_offset)

    # Formatting the axes' labels and ticks
    for ax in pp.axes.flat:
        ax.set_xlabel(ax.get_xlabel(), fontsize=font_size,
                      rotation=0, labelpad=0.66*font_size)
        ax.set_ylabel(ax.get_ylabel(), fontsize=font_size,
                      rotation=90, labelpad=0.66*font_size)
        ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(labelsize=0.83*font_size, pad=0.33*font_size)
        ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(labelsize=0.83*font_size, pad=0.33*font_size)

def cust_hist(data, figsize_w=8, figsize_h=6,
              title=None, title_fs=16, title_offset=20,
              rem_borders=False,
              x_label=None, xlabel_fs=12,
              n_bins=10, col_numb=0):
    """
    This function plots a histogram for the provided data and customizes
    the way the chart looks by using the value of the provided parameters.

    Keyword arguments:
    data            -- A pandas Series (mandatory)
    figsize_w       -- The width of the plot area
    figsize_w       -- The height of the plot area
    title           -- A string containing the title of the chart
    title_fs        -- The title font size
    title_offset    -- The distance between the title and the top of the chart
    rem_borders     -- If True, the top and right borders are removed
                       (default: False)
    x_label         -- Label for the x-axis (string)
    xlabel_fs       -- x axis labels' font size
    n_bins          -- An integer giving the numner of bins or
                       a list giving the bin edges
                       (all but the last interval are open to the right)
    col_numb        -- An integer between 0 and 9 that indicated the
                       seaborn-deep color to be used for the plot
    """

    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Creating a new figure
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))
    # Defining the used style
    color_list = sns.color_palette(palette='deep')
    # Removing the top and right borders if so defined
    if rem_borders is True:
        plt.gca().spines['top'].set_visible(False)
        plt.gca().spines['right'].set_visible(False)

    # Adding a title (with some distance to the top of the plot)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=title_fs, pad=title_offset)

    # Creating the histogram
    plt.hist(data, bins=n_bins, color=color_list[col_numb])

    # If a label for the x axis is provided, showing it on the x axis
    if x_label:
        plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=xlabel_fs)

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.show()

def plot_cust_bar(data,
                  figsize_w=8, figsize_h=6,
                  frame=True, grid=False,
                  ref_font_size=12,
                  title_text=None,
                  title_offset=20,
                  color_numb=0,
                  categ_labels=True,
                  labels=None,
                  rot=0,
                  show_values=False,
                  omitted_value=0,
                  percent=False,
                  value_offset=1,
                  visible_digits=2):
    """
    This function plots a bar charts for the provided data with
    the provided labels and settings.

    Keyword arguments:
    data            -- A list that contains sorted data of a categorical series
                       (mandatory)
    figsize_w       -- The width of the plot area
    figsize_h       -- The height of the plot area
    frame           -- If False, the figure frame is omitted as well as
                       ticks and labels on the y axis (default is True)
    grid            -- If True a horizontal grid is displayed. It works
                       only when frame=True (default is False)
    ref_font_size   -- Reference font size used for all the fonts
    title_text      -- A string containing the title of the chart
    title_offset    -- The offset of the title from the rest of the plot
    color_numb      -- An integer between 0 and 9 that indicated the
                       seaborn-deep color to be used for the bars
    categ_labels    -- A boolean variable that defines if category labels
                       shall appear (on the x-axis)
    labels          -- List of category labels (strings). Used only if
                       categ_labels=True.
                       They override the existing lables
    rot             -- The rotation of the x axsis label (numerical)
                       (the default is horizontal)
    show_values     -- If True, then numeric value labels will be shown on
                       each bar (default is False)
    omitted_value   -- The max value that shall not be shown in the bar
    percent         -- If true, it indicates that the values are in percentage
                       (default is False)
    value_offset    -- Used to position the bar values in the plott
    visible_digits  -- Integer defining the number of decimal digits
                       to be seen in the value labels (the default is 2)
    """

    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Finding the number of categories
    cat_number = len(data)

    # Defining the suffix to be shown in the bar values
    if percent:
        p = '%'
    else:
        p = ""

    # Preparing the indexes for the x axis
    ind = list(range(cat_number))

    # Creating a new figure
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))
    # Defining the used style
    color_list = sns.color_palette(palette='deep')

    # Removing x axis ticks
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_ticks_position('none')

    if not frame:
        # Removing the borders, if so defined
        sns.despine(top=True, right=True, left=True, bottom=True)
        # Removing ticks and values in the y axes
        plt.gca().axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    elif grid:
        # Showing a horizontal grig, if so defined
        plt.gca().yaxis.grid(color='grey', alpha=0.25,
                             linestyle='-', linewidth=1)

    # Adding a title (with some distance to the top of the plot)
    plt.title(title_text, fontsize=ref_font_size*1.33, pad=title_offset)

    # Creating the bar plot
    plot = plt.bar(ind, data, color=color_list[color_numb])

    # Showing category labels them on the x axes, if so defined
    if categ_labels:
        # Overriding the index value if category labels are provided
        if labels:
            plt.xticks(ind, labels, fontsize=ref_font_size, rotation=rot)
        else:
            plt.xticks(ind, data.index.tolist(),
                       fontsize=ref_font_size, rotation=rot)
    else:
        # Removing ticks and values in the x axes
        plt.gca().axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)

    # Showing the bar values, if so defined
    if show_values:
        # Iterating through the bars in the plot
        for bar in plot:
            # Getting bar height and width
            w, h = bar.get_width(), bar.get_height()
            # Printing the values only if they are bigger than the defined value
            if h > omitted_value:
                # Positioning the text in the centre of the bar horizontally
                # and on top of the bar with an offset vertically
                plt.text(bar.get_x() + w/2, bar.get_y() + h + value_offset,
                         "{}".format(round(h, visible_digits))+p,
                         fontsize=ref_font_size,
                         ha="center", va="baseline")

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.show()

    """

    show_values     -- If True, then numeric value labels will be shown on
                       each bar (default is False)
    omitted_value   -- The max value that shall not be shown in the bar
    percent         -- If true, it indicates that the values are in percentage
                       (default is False)
    value_offset    -- Used to position the bar values in the plott
    visible_digits  -- Integer defining the number of decimal digits
                       to be seen in the value labels (the default is 2)
    leg_list        -- A list containing the content of the legend
    leg_loc         -- A integer from 0 to 9 indicating the location of the
                       legend
    """

    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Defining the suffix to be shown in the bar values
    if percent:
        p = '%'
    else:
        p = ""

    # Defining the vertical width of the bars
    bars_width = 1/4

    # Creating a new figure
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))
    # Defining the used style
    color_list = sns.color_palette(palette='deep')

    # Removing y axis ticks
    plt.gca().yaxis.set_ticks_position('none')

    if frame is False:
        # Removing the borders, if so defined
        sns.despine(top=True, right=True, left=True, bottom=True)
        # Removing ticks and values in the x axes
        plt.gca().axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
    elif grid:
        # Showing a vertical grig, if so defined
        plt.gca().xaxis.grid(color='grey', alpha=0.25,
                             linestyle='-', linewidth=1)

    # Adding a title (with some distance to the top of the plot)
    plt.title(title_text, fontsize=ref_font_size*1.33,
              loc='center', pad=title_offset)

    # Creating the bar plot
    plot1 = plt.barh([x + bars_width for x in range(len(data1))],
                     data1,
                     height=bars_width,
                     color=color_list[color_numb1])
    plot2 = plt.barh([x for x in range(len(data2))],
                     data2,
                     height=bars_width,
                     color=color_list[color_numb2])
    plot3 = plt.barh([x - bars_width for x in range(len(data3))],
                     data3,
                     height=bars_width,
                     color=color_list[color_numb3])
    plots = [plot1, plot2, plot3]

    # Showing category labels them on the y axes, if so defined
    if categ_labels:
        # Overriding the index value if category labels are provided
        if labels:
            plt.yticks(range(len(labels)), labels,
                       fontsize=ref_font_size, rotation=rot)
        else:
            plt.yticks(list(range(len(data1))),
                       data1.index.tolist(),
                       fontsize=ref_font_size,
                       rotation=rot)
    else:
        # Removing ticks and values in the y axes
        plt.gca().axes.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)

    # Showing the bar values, if so defined
    if show_values:
        # Iterating through the three sets of bars
        for plot in plots:
            # Iterating through the bars in each set
            for bar in plot:
                # Getting bar height and width
                w, h = bar.get_width(), bar.get_height()
                # Printing the values only if they are bigger than
                # the defined value
                if w > omitted_value:
                    # Positioning the text in the centre of the bar vertically
                    # and on the right of the bar with an offset horizontally
                    plt.text(bar.get_x() + w + value_offset, bar.get_y() + h/2,
                             "{}".format(round(w, visible_digits))+p,
                             fontsize=ref_font_size,
                             ha="left", va="center")

    # Adding a legend
    if leg_list:
        fig.legend(leg_list,
                   frameon=False,
                   fontsize=ref_font_size*0.83,
                   loc=leg_loc)

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.show()

def lat_long_scatter_plot(x1, y1,
                          figsize_w=8, figsize_h=6,

    """

    Keyword arguments:

def plot_feature_importances(model, feature_names,
                             figsize_w=8, figsize_h=12,
                             ref_font_size=12,
                             title_offset=0,
                             feat_numb=10,
                             value_offset=0,
                             visible_digits=2):

    """
    This function allows to visualize a horizontal bar chart containing
    the feature importance of a decision tree.
    The features are listed in decreasing importance order.

    Keyword arguments:
    model           -- A fitted model
    feature_names   -- A list of strings containing the feature names
    figsize_w       -- The width of the plot area
    figsize_h       -- The height of the plot area
    feat_numb       -- The number of features that shall be visualized
                       (default = 10).
                       This is useful for high dimensional datasets.
    value_offset    -- Used to position the bar values in the plot
    visible_digits  -- Integer defining the number of decimal digits
                       to be seen in the value labels (the default is 2)
    """

    import numpy as np
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Calculate feature importances
    importances = model.feature_importances_  # numpy.ndarray
    # Sorting feature importances in descending order
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]
    # Rearranging the feature names so they match the sorted feature importances
    feat_names = [feature_names[i] for i in indices]  # list
    # Selecting the top of the list
    top_feats = feat_names[0:feat_numb]
    top_import = importances[indices][0:feat_numb]
    # Sorting feature importances of the most important features in
    # ascending order
    top_import = np.sort(top_import)[::1]
    # Rearranging the feature names accordingly
    top_feats = list(reversed(top_feats))

    # Creating a plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))

    # Removing the borders
    for spine in plt.gca().spines.values():
        spine.set_visible(False)
    # Removing ticks and values in the x axis
    plt.gca().axes.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
    # Removing y axes ticks
    plt.gca().yaxis.set_ticks_position('none')

    # Adding a title
    plt.title("Feature importance for the most influential features",
              fontsize=ref_font_size*1.33, pad=title_offset)
    # Adding axses labels
    plt.ylabel("Feature name", fontsize=ref_font_size)
    # Adding the feature names as y-axis tick labels
    plt.yticks(np.arange(feat_numb), top_feats, fontsize=ref_font_size*0.83)

    # Adding horizontal bars
    plot = plt.barh(list(range(feat_numb)), top_import)

    # Adding bar labels with the actual bar lenght value
    # Iterating through the bars in the plot
    for bar in plot:
        # Getting bar height and width
        w, h = bar.get_width(), bar.get_height()
        # Positioning the text in the centre of the bar vertically
        # and on the right of the bar with an offset horizontally
        plt.text(bar.get_x() + w + value_offset, bar.get_y() + h/2,
                 "{}".format(round(w, visible_digits)), fontsize=ref_font_size,
                 ha="left", va="center")

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def ROC_Curve(*parameters,
              figsize_w=8, figsize_h=6,
              ref_font_size=12,
              title="ROC curve",
              title_offset=20,
              col_numb=0):
    """
    This function plots a lineplot for the provided data and customizes
    the way the chart looks by using the value of the provided parameters.
    The plot is optimized to show a ROC curve and the ROC score
    and it can plot up several different curves

    Keyword arguments:
    parameters       -- A tuple containing 4 values:
                        - fpr (an array containing the false positive rate),
                        - tpr (an array containing the true positive rate),
                        - roc_auc (a float containing the value of
                        the area under the curve)
                        - a string containingt ext to be inserted in the label
                        of the legend
                        (mandatory - more than a tuple can be provided)
    figsize_w        -- The width of the plot area
    figsize_w        -- The height of the plot area
    ref_font_size    -- The reference font size
    title            -- A string containing the title of the chart
    title_offset     -- Distance between the title and the top of the chart
    col_numb         -- An integer (from 0 to 9) selecting the seaborn-deep
                        color of the first curve
    """

    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import seaborn as sns

    # Creating a new figure
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsize_w, figsize_h))

    # Defining the used style
    color_list = sns.color_palette(palette='deep')

    # Setting limits for the axses
    plt.gca().set_xlim(-0.01, 1.0)
    plt.gca().set_ylim(-0.01, 1.0)

    # Adding a title (with some distance to the top of the plot)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=ref_font_size*1.33, pad=title_offset)

    # Creating the ROC line plot and adding a label with the AUC value
    # for each provided tupe of values
    col = col_numb
    for param in parameters:
        fpr = param[0]
        tpr = param[1]
        roc_auc = param[2]
        label_text = param[3]
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr,
                 linewidth=3, color=color_list[col],
                 label=label_text + " (area = {:0.4f})".format(roc_auc))
        # Setting the color to the next one for the next loop
        if col <= 8:
            col += 1
        else:
            col = 0
    # Adding a legend with the label and AUC value
    plt.legend(loc='lower right', fontsize=ref_font_size*0.83)
    # Adding the baseline
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],
             color=color_list[7], linewidth=3, linestyle='--')

    # Showing x axis label
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate", fontsize=ref_font_size)
    # Showing y axis label
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate", fontsize=ref_font_size)

    # Showing the plot without additional text
    plt.show()

5.2. Preliminary Data Analysis¶

5.2.1. Summary¶

The train dataset has 250306 entries. The test dataset has 61001 entries. This correspond to a 80% / 20% train / test split.

However, the train set has 90426 entries will null value in the variable compliance (that corresponds to about 36% of the entries). Those are the entries corresponding to violators that were found not responsible. This leaves only 159880 entries in the train dataset corresponding to responsible violators. By considering only those entries, the train / test split is actually 72% / 28 %.

In order to avoid data leakage, the test data set contains entries that are belonging time-wise to the period after a timestamp cutoff (which is at the end of year 2011).

Therefore, train.csv contains tickets issued in the period 2004-2011 whereas test.csv contains tickets issued in the period 2012-2016.

Note that there are three data insertion mistakes in the ticket_issued_date column of the train dataset.

Each row in these two files corresponds to a single blight ticket, and includes information about when, where, why, by whom and to whom each ticket was issued.

The target variable is compliance, which is True if the ticket was paid early, on time, or within one month of the hearing date, False if the ticket was paid later than one month after the hearing date or not at all, and Null if the violator was found not responsible. This variable, as well as a handful of other variables that will not be available at test-time, are only included in train.csv.

The addresses dataset contains 311307 entries, that is the sum of the entries in the train dataset (250306) and the entries in the test dataset (61001). There are 121769 unique addresses in the address dataset, which is the same as the number of entries of the latlons dataset. This means that in the latlons dataset there are entries for every ticket id.

45.652 out of 119. 992 violators have had more than 1 accident. 1864 of them have had more than 10 accidents and 19 of them have had more than 100 accidents.

5.2.2. Data fields¶

train.csv & test.csv:

  • ticket_id: unique identifier for blight tickets
  • agency_name: Agency that issued the ticket
  • inspector_name: Name of the inspector that issued the ticket
  • violator_name: Name of the person/organization that the ticket was issued to
  • violation_street_number, violation_street_name, violation_zip_code: Address where the violation occurred
  • mailing_address_str_number, mailing_address_str_name, city, state, zip_code, non_us_str_code, country: Mailing address of the violator
  • ticket_issued_date: Date and time the ticket was issued
  • hearing_date: Date and time the violator's hearing was scheduled (if the property owner complies before the hearing, the fine is withdrawn)
  • violation_code, violation_description: Type of violation
  • disposition: Judgment and judgement type
  • fine_amount: Violation fine amount, excluding fees
  • admin_fee: 20 dollars fee assigned to responsible judgements
  • state_fee: 10 dollars fee assigned to responsible judgments
  • late_fee: 10% fee assigned to responsible judgments (this penality is imposed if the propriety owner is found responsible at hearing and the fine and fees imposed are not paid by the hearing date)
  • discount_amount: discount applied, if any
  • clean_up_cost: DPW clean-up or graffiti removal cost
  • judgment_amount: Sum of all fines and fees
  • grafitti_status: Flag for graffiti violations

train.csv only:

  • payment_amount: Amount paid, if any
  • payment_date: Date payment was made, if it was received
  • payment_status: Current payment status as of Feb 1 2017
  • balance_due: Fines and fees still owed
  • collection_status: Flag for payments in collections
  • compliance [target variable for prediction]
    • Null = Not responsible
    • 0 = Responsible, non-compliant
    • 1 = Responsible, compliant
  • compliance_detail: More information on why each ticket was marked compliant or non-compliant

addresses.csv only:

  • ticket_id
  • address: a combination of violation_street_number and violation_street_name

latlonss.csv only:

  • address
  • lat: latitude corresponding to the violation address
  • lon: longitude corresponding to the violation address

# Finding the occurrencies of each violator name

# The interval specified below are open to the left and closed to the right
limits = [0, 1, 10, 100, 100000]

                        right=True, include_lowest=False)

# Creating a new categorical binary variable based on discount_amount variables
# (all cells of the column with value different from 0.0 are converted into value 'Fee',
# all cells of the column with value 0.0 are converted into value 'No fee')
train_modified['discount'] = train_modified['discount_amount']
train_modified.loc[train_modified['discount'] != 0.0, 'discount'] = 'Discount'
train_modified.loc[train_modified['discount'] == 0.0, 'discount'] = 'No discount'

train_modified['discount_percentage'] = train_modified['discount_amount']/\

# Converting the date related variable to datetime64
train_modified['ticket_issued_date'] = pd.to_datetime(train_modified['ticket_issued_date'])

train_modified['year'] = train_modified['ticket_issued_date'].dt.year

# Eliminating the ticket_issued_date variable
del train_modified['ticket_issued_date']

train_modified['year_cat'] = train_modified['year'].astype('category')

train_modified['month_cat'] = train_modified['month'].astype('category')

5.4. Data Cleansing¶

5.4.1. Summary¶

Columns like violation_zip_code, non_us_str_code and grafiti_status are not very useful due to the high density of null values.

The entry that has a null value in the variable fine_amount of the train dataset is related to a non-responsible violator so it is not a useful entry for the prediction model.

There are 7 entries in latlons dataset with null lat and lon values. Those correspond to 8 ticket ids so the coordinates dataframe has 8 null values. 3 of those ticket ids are in the train dataset. The remaining 5 are in the test dataset.

The entries with null values in compliance (in the train_coord dataset) contain the one entry with null value in fine_amount, one of the three entries with null coordinates and two of the three entries with incorrect date.

Among the 34 entries with null values in the violator category (those are the entries that have a null value in the violator name in the original training dataset), 8 of them have null values also in the compliance variable and therefore will not be used to fit the model.

There is clear some outlier at 10.000 in the variable fine_amount (in the train dataset) but it is not a typing mistake since according to this page in the City of Detroit website, fines can go up to that amount.

The entries related to null values in the compliance column (entries related to non-responsible violators), entries with null values in the coordinates as well as the three entries with incorrect date haven been cleaned.

They are no miss-spelled addresses in the address column.

5.4.5. Verifying there are no miss-typed addresses¶

In [47]:
# THIS CELL TAKES ABOUT 30 MINUTES TO RUN!

import datetime as dt

# Initializing data to provide consolle feedback
start_time = dt.datetime.now()
print ("Script start time:", start_time)
total = len(train_cleaned)
feedb_int = 10000

# Fetching the street number
numbers = train_cleaned['violation_street_number']
# Fetching the street name in lower letters
streets = train_cleaned['violation_street_name'].str.lower()

# Initializing an empty dataframe
corr_addr = pd.DataFrame()
# Iterating through all the rows of the train_cleaned dataframe
for i in list(range(total)):
    # Fetching the cell in the address column
    cell = train_cleaned.loc[train_cleaned.index[i], ['address']]
    # Checking if the cell contains the number and the street name separated
    # by a space and followed by a comma
    # Then storing the result in a boolean variable in a Series of lenght 1 
    number = numbers.loc[numbers.index[i]].astype('str')
    street = streets.loc[streets.index[i]]
    correct = cell.str.contains(number + " " + street + ",")
    # Adding the corresponding ticket_id to a Series
    corr_addr.at[i, 'ticket_id'] = train_cleaned.loc[train_cleaned.index[i],
                                                     ['ticket_id']][0]
    # Adding the value of the lenght 1 Series above to the Series
    corr_addr.at[i, 'correct_address'] = correct[0]
    # Checking if it it time to update consolle feebback
    if i != 0 and i%feedb_int == 0:
        print(i, "entries handled at", dt.datetime.now())

# Converting the column 'ticket_id' into integer
corr_addr['ticket_id'] = corr_addr['ticket_id'].astype('int')

# Providing consolle feedback
end_time = dt.datetime.now()
print ("Script end time:", end_time)
print ("Script duration:", end_time - start_time)

5.5. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

5.5.1. Summary¶

This analysis confirms the choice of the selected variables and provides useful insights for the selecting the predictions models to be tested.

The maximum and minimum values of the numerical variables differ quite a lot for the different variables, so for all those methods that require feature normalization, it is important to process the data accordingly.

92.75% of the violators are not compliant. This means that they have not paid by a month after the hearing date. Among compliant violators, 54.32% pays after the hearing date, 33.46% pays by the hearing date and 8.55% pays before the hearing date. Among non-compliant violators 87.18% does not pay at all and 12.82% pays later than one month after the hearing date.

Most of the fines are below 500. The distribution of values is strongly skewed to the right with some outlier around 10000.

About disposition: 89.73% of the no compliant violators are classified as "responsible by default". The compliant violators are more evenly distributed also among the categories of "responsible by admission" and "responsible by determination".

The Department of Public Work Agency has issued the biggest amount of fines to responsible violators (59.96%). The success of each agency to collect the fine has been comparable and Detroit Police Department is the agency that has been more successful with a 13.15% of compliant violators.

The percentage of non-complaint cases within each violator category grows steadily by moving to categories that contain more frequent violators.

Over 90% of the entries related to responsible violators have a late fee. Among the complaint violators, almost half have had a late fee (therefore, almost half of them has paid within one month of the hearing date). Among non-compliant violators, most of them have had the fee.

A discount has been applied only to 0.74% of the cases related to responsible violators. This percentage increases to 9.68% by considering only the compliant violators.

There are few locations which are far from the district. Most of those locations are related to non-compliant violators.

5.5.4. Discount¶

All compliant violators that have paid before the hearing date have had a discount. However, not all the violators that have had a discount are early payers.

The 196 entries with null discount percentage in train_modified data set correspond to the 195 entries with zero fine_amount and to the entry with null fine_amount. The entries with zero fine_amount are all related to compliant violators whose fine has been waived.

For those who have had the discount, the amount varies between 10 and 12%. Therefore, the variable discount_percentage will not be likely a useful predictor.

5.5.5. Late fee¶

Among the responsible violators that have no late fee, there are both compliant and non-compliant violators. This ensures that this variable is not leading to data leakage when fitting a prediction model. The non-complaint violators have not paid at all or have paid more than one month after the hearing date (in this case they should have had the late fee). The compliant violators have either paid in full or no payment was applicable.

5.6. Preparing Data for Fitting Prediction Models¶

5.6.1. Summary¶

Variables which are not useful predictors because they contain always the same value or because have many zero values or because they would lead to a huge number of variables with many zero values (categorical variables with many distinct values) have been dropped from the data set to be used for model prediction. The same has been done for variables that are not considered to be useful predictors because of their meaning or because they are redundant (for example, text variables whose values map one to one to categorical variables containing codes).

The remaining features have been separated from the target variable.

Modifications have been done to the test dataset in order to align it with the modifications done to the training data set.

Finally, a validation data set has been extracted from the train dataset to be used for model evaluation.

Also, the features have been normalized and stored in separate data sets to be used with models that require feature normalization (like linear models).

5.6.3. Discarded Variables¶

The variable ticket_id is not a useful predictor. The violator_name has been refactorized in the violator_cat variable.

The violation_street_number, violation_street_name and violation_zip_code are factorized in the lat and lon variables. Also, the variable violation_zip_code is always null in the train dataset. The variables violation_street_number and violation_street_name have been added temporarily to the modified dataframe to check the correct addresses in the cleansing phase but they have been discarded in the selected dataframe.

Using the mailing_address_street_name and the mailing_address_street_number would not have added considerable benefits and would have resulted in an excessive high number of categorical variables containing a lot of null entries. The same applies to the city and zip_code. It has been decided not to use the variable state since it would have added additional indicator variables and it would have caused the deletion of a comparable number of entries due to null values.

non_us_str_code and country would not have been very useful since almost all the violators' mail addresses are in US.

Using ticket_issued_date and hearing_date to calculate the number of days from the day the ticket has been issued to the day that has been fixed for the hearing would have been very useful. Unfortunately, the variable hearing_date contains a lot of date entry errors (for example, 171 entries have the hearing date before the ticket issued date) and therefore it would not have been a reliable estimator. Also, the variable contains 12491 null values, which would have led to discard about 5% of the training data.

The variables inspector_name and violation_code could potentially be useful predictors but they are categorical variables containing a big number of categories and therefore they would result in adding of many sparse variables without adding much value.

The variable violation_description is basically the textual version of the violation code.

The variables admin_fee and state_fee are not useful variables since such fees are asked to each responsible violator.

The variable judgment_amount does not give any additional information since it is the sum of fine_amount, admin_fee, state_fee and late_fee.

The variable grafitti_status has all null values except one. The variable clean_up_cost is always zero.

# Changing the datatype of hearing_date from object to datetime64
hearing_date_dateformat = pd.to_datetime(train['hearing_date'])
ticket_issued_date_dateformat = pd.to_datetime(train['ticket_issued_date'])
# Calculating the number of days between ticket issued date and hearing date
time_to_hearing = hearing_date_dateformat - ticket_issued_date_dateformat
# Extracting the days
days_to_hearing = time_to_hearing.dt.days
# Calculating how many instances have negative differences
negative_diff = days_to_hearing[days_to_hearing < 0].count()
# Calculating how many instances have too high values
too_high_values = days_to_hearing[days_to_hearing > 365].count()
# Calculating how many instances have too small values
too_low_values = days_to_hearing[days_to_hearing < 30].count()
# Visualizing the results
print("There are {} entries where the hearing date is before the ticket issued date.\n\n"\
      "There are {} entries where the hearing date is more than one year "\
      "in the future compared to the ticket issued date.\n\n"\
      "There are {} entries where the hearing date is less than one month "\
      "in the future compared to the ticket issued date.".format(negative_diff,

6. Fitting Different Prediction Models ¶

6.1. Summary¶

This is a classification problem.

Due to the categorical variables, we have a sparse data set (half the features have a lot of zero values). Therefore, few of the selected prediction models are of the Linear Models family. On the other hand, due to the good prediction performance of ensemble methods, also Random Forest and Gradient Boosted Decision Trees methods are used. Neural networks are not used in order to limit the needed run time.

As an exploratory model, a simple Decision Tree model is used.

Since there are a lot of unbalanced classes, accuracy is not a useful evaluation metrics. In this project ROC curves are used. Accuracy is used as a preliminary metrics to adjust model parameters in order to avoid the model overfits.

6.2. Selected Evaluation Metrics¶

A single number metric will be used for model evaluation: the Area Under the Curve (AUC).

The Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (ROC) has False Positive Rate (FPR) in the x axis and True Positive Rate (TPR) in the y axis.

TPR represents the fraction of positive instances identified correctly as positive (TPR = TP / (TP + FN)).

FPR represents the fraction of all negative instances incorrectly classified as positive (FPR = FP / (TN + FP)).

The Area under the curve represents the probability that the classifier will assign a higher score to a randomly chosen positive example than to a randomly chosen negative example.

To check how much the model overfits, for each model an overfitting indicator is calculated as the difference of the auc score on the training set and the auc score on the validation set, divided by the auc score on the validation set, in percentage. Ideally, this overfitting indicator is zero. However, values smaller that 1% are somehow acceptable.

6.3. Code to be run before model fitting¶

Here is the code that needs to be run to dump and process the data before fitting the prediction models. This is useful when modifying the machine learning part of this notebook without touching the data preparation part.

train_modified['ticket_issued_date'] = pd.to_datetime(train_modified['ticket_issued_date'])
# Extracting the year and the month from ticket_issued_date
train_modified['year'] = train_modified['ticket_issued_date'].dt.year
train_modified['month'] = train_modified['ticket_issued_date'].dt.month
# Eliminating the ticket_issued_date variable
del train_modified['ticket_issued_date']
# Converting violation_street_number into the correct datatype
train_modified['violation_street_number'] = train_modified['violation_street_number'].\
                                            astype('int')

# *** Cleaning Data ***

# Eliminating the entries in the train dataset containing data insertion mistakes
# in the ticket_issued_date column
train_cleaned = train_modified[(train_modified['year'] != 1938) & 
                               (train_modified['year'] != 1963) & 
                               (train_modified['year'] != 1988)]
# Eliminating entries with null values in compliance
train_cleaned = train_cleaned[pd.notnull(train_cleaned['compliance'])]

# Filling the null values of lat and lon with the mean values in the column
train_cleaned['lat'] = train_cleaned['lat'].fillna(train_cleaned['lat'].mean())
train_cleaned['lon'] = train_cleaned['lon'].fillna(train_cleaned['lon'].mean())
# Filling the null values of violator_cat with the most recurring value of the category
train_cleaned['violator_cat'] = train_cleaned['violator_cat'].\
fillna(train_cleaned['violator_cat'].value_counts().idxmax())

# Converting the target value into integer type
train_cleaned['compliance'] = train_cleaned['compliance'].astype('int')

# *** Preparing Data for Fitting Predicion Models ***

# Selecting the variables to be used in the training data set

                                      'agency_name',
                                      'year',

                                      'violator_cat',
                                      'lat',

The AUC value is surprisingly good. This is a good sign since it might mean that the feature selection is good. With good quality data also a simple and imperfect model can reach decent evaluation score values.

According to this preliminary analysis, the most useful predictors are:

  • whether there has been no late fine
  • whether the responsible violator has admitted the responsibility
  • whether there has been a discount

With a considerable smaller influence, there are also the following predictors:

  • the fine amount
  • whether the violator is a first-time offender

6.7. Random Forest¶

It is an ensemble model, that is, a model that takes multiple individual learning models and combines them to produce an aggregate model that is more powerful than any of its individual learning models alone. This allows averaging out the individual mistakes of the individual models to reduce the risk of overfitting while maintaining strong prediction performance.

Random Forest builds different trees by introducing random variation into the process of building each tree. First, the data used to build each tree is selected randomly and second, the features chosen in each split are also randomly selected.

Each tree is built from a different bootstrap sample. If a training set has N instances, a bootstrap sample of size N is created by repeatedly picking one of the N dataset rows at random with replacement N times.

Like for decision trees, the parameters max_depth, min_samples_split and min_samples_leaf are used to control overfitting.

6.8. Gradient Boosted Decision Trees¶

Ii is also an ensemble model.

The gradient boosted decision trees method builds a series of trees where each tree is trained so that it attempts to correct the mistakes of the previous tree in the series.

The paramater is the learning_rate controls how hard each new tree tries to correct the remaining mistakes from the previous round. A high learning rate means more complex trees. This parameter, together with the max_depth parameter, is used to control overfitting.

7. Selecting the Model ¶

Decison Tree (AUC = 0.8144) scores better than Logistic Regression (AUC = 0.7913) with all values of C.

Linear Support Vector Machines gives similar results as Logistic Regression for different values of C (AUC = 0.7918).

Random Forest provides a good score (AUC = 0.8161).

Gradient Boosted Decision Trees provides the best result (AUC = 0.8227), which is not so bad, by considering that the highest score obtained by participants in the kaggle competition with the test dataset is 0.83392.

Since the overfit indicator of the fitted Gradient Boosted Decision Trees model is 0.72%, it is expected that on the test set the auc value might decrease to 0.8168, which is still quite acceptable.

9. Conclusions ¶

Data has been manipulated by merging different data sets and by creating new features.

A new categorical variable has been created to divide violators in 4 classes based on the amount of violations.

Other two categorical variables have been created to indicate whether there has been a late fee and whether there has been a discount (since the late fee is always a fixed percentage of the fine amount and the discount, when applied, it is within a very narrow percentage range).

Year and month have been extracted from the ticket issued date.

Then data has been cleansed.

After checking null values and outliers in the train data set, three entries with wrong dara in the ticket issued date have been eliminated from the train dataset.

The entries with finite value in the compliance (entries related to responsible violators) have been selected from the train dataset. Then, the few entries with null values on the coordinates and in the violator category variable have been filled by using the mean for the numerical variables and the most frequent value for the categorical variable.

It has been verified that there were no miss-spelled addresses in the additional files.

An exploratory data analysis has been done to check extreme values and the consequent need for normalization, to help in the selection of the potential predictors (features) and to give hints about the prediction methods that would be most likely successful.

This analysis has also helped to confirm that the selected features (like discount and late fee) would not introduce risks of data leakage.

The result of this analysis included a comprehensive list of plots.

As a result of this work, the following features have been selected:

  • agency_name (categorical)
  • year (numerical)
  • month (numerical)
  • violator_cat (categorical)
  • lat (numerical)
  • lon (numerical)
  • disposition (categorical)
  • fine_amount (numerical)
  • late_fee (categorical)
  • discount (categorical)

In addition, ticket_id has been selected for consistency with the test dataset and the target value (compliance) has been isolated in a separate dataset.

Variables which are not useful predictors because they contain always the same value or because have many zero values or because they would lead to a huge number of variables with many zero values have been dropped. The same has been done for variables that are not considered to be useful predictors because of their meaning or because they are redundant.

The data has been further prepared for machine learning.

The category names in the categorical variables have been aligned in the train and the test data sets.

The categorical variables have been converted into indicator variables.

Modifications have been done to the test dataset in order to align it with the modifications done to the training data set.

Finally, a validation data set has been extracted from the train dataset to be used for model evaluation.

The models to be tried and the evaluation metrics to be used have been identified.

The result was a dataset with 32 features, containing sparse data. Therefore, a couple of linear models (Logistic Regression and Linear Support Vector Machines) have been tried. Before applying the linear models, the features have been normalized. Also, a Decision Tree has been used as an explorative prediction model. A couple of ensemble models (Random Forest and Gradient Boosted Decision Threes) have been fit as well.

Accuracy was not a useful evaluation metrics due to the presence of many unbalanced classes and the AUC (area under the ROC curve) has been used to evaluate the different models.

The models have been created and evaluated.

Care has been taken when tuning the different models that the AUC in the train set was not higher than 1% compared to the AUC value in the validation set, in order to limit overfitting.

Both the extensive data preparation and the careful parameter tuning have paid back.

Decision tree has given a surprising good AUC value on the validation set (AUC = 0.8144) with a reasonably low overfit coefficient (0.63%).

The liner models have performed worst (Logistic Regression gave an AUC of 0.7913 and Linear Support Vector Machines gave an AUC of 0.7918).

Random Forest provided an AUC of 0.8161 while Gradient Boosted Decision Trees gave the best result of 0.8227 on the validation data set with a overfit coefficient of 0.72%.

This has led to an AUC of 0.8221 on the test set, which is a quite good result by considering that the highest score obtained by participants in the kaggle competition with the test dataset was 0.83392 and the third best value was 0.8215.

10. Annex: Pipeline code ¶

This section contains just the code needed to retrieve the data, to prepare and clean it for fitting the selected prediction mode and to apply the selected prediction model by making a prediction with test data.

In [166]:
# Importing the needed packages
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier

def blight_model():
    
    # Data Dumping
    
    # Training data set
    train = pd.read_csv('readonly/train.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1",
                        low_memory=False)
    # Test data set
    test = pd.read_csv('readonly/test.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
    # Additional files
    addresses = pd.read_csv('readonly/addresses.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
    latlons = pd.read_csv('readonly/latlons.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1")
    
    # Data Preparation

    # Merging address and latlons dataframes with address as a key (left join)
    coordinates = pd.merge(addresses, latlons, how='left',
                           left_on='address', right_on='address')
    # Merging the train dataset with the coordinates dataset (left join)
    # with ticket_id as a key
    train_coord = pd.merge(train, coordinates, how='left',
                           left_on='ticket_id', right_on='ticket_id')
    # Merging the test dataset with the coordinates dataset (left join)
    # with ticket_id as a key
    test_coord = pd.merge(test, coordinates, how='left',
                          left_on='ticket_id', right_on='ticket_id')

    # Finding the occurrencies of each violator name
    viol_occ = train['violator_name'].value_counts()
    # Creating  a new variable containing the violator category
    # The interval specified below are open to the left and closed to the right
    limits = [0, 1, 10, 100, 100000]
    labels = ['Only 1', 'More than 1', 'More than 10', 'More than 100']
    violator_cat_s = pd.cut(viol_occ, bins=limits, labels=labels, 
                            right=True, include_lowest=False)
    # Converting the series into a dataframe and renaming the column
    violator_cat_d = violator_cat_s.to_frame().\
    rename(columns={"violator_name": "violator_cat"})
    # Merging the dataframe containing the violator categories with the train_coor dataset
    # by using violator_name as am index for train_coor (right join)
    train_modified = pd.merge(violator_cat_d, train_coord, how='right',
                              left_index=True, right_on='violator_name')

    # Creating a new dataframe to be used in the exploratory data analysis phase
    train_mod = train_modified.loc[:,['ticket_id',
                                      'agency_name',
                                      'ticket_issued_date',
                                      'violator_cat',
                                      'lat',
                                      'lon',
                                      'disposition',
                                      'fine_amount',
                                      'late_fee',
                                      'discount_amount',
                                      'compliance']]
    # Converting the categorical variables into the correct datatype
    train_mod['agency_name'] = train_mod['agency_name'].astype('category')
    train_mod['disposition'] = train_mod['disposition'].astype('category')
    # Converting late_fee variable into categorical binary variables
    # (all cells of the column with value different from 0.0 are converted into value 'Fee',
    # all cells of the column with value 0.0 are converted into value 'No fee')
    # Then the type is changed into categorical
    train_mod.loc[train_mod['late_fee'] != 0.0, 'late_fee'] = 'Fee'
    train_mod.loc[train_mod['late_fee'] == 0.0, 'late_fee'] = 'No fee'
    train_mod['late_fee'] = train_mod['late_fee'].astype('category')
    # Creating a new categorical binary variable based on discount_amount variables
    # (all cells of the column with value different from 0.0 are converted into value 'Fee',
    # all cells of the column with value 0.0 are converted into value 'No fee')
    train_mod['discount'] = train_mod['discount_amount']
    train_mod.loc[train_mod['discount'] != 0.0, 'discount'] = 'Discount'
    train_mod.loc[train_mod['discount'] == 0.0, 'discount'] = 'No discount'
    train_mod['discount'] = train_mod['discount'].astype('category')
    # Creating a new continuos variable containing the percentage of discount
    # compared to the fine_amount
    train_mod['discount_percentage'] = train_mod['discount_amount']/\
                                       train_mod['fine_amount']*100
    # Converting the date related variable to datetime64
    train_mod['ticket_issued_date'] = pd.to_datetime(train_mod['ticket_issued_date'])
    # Extracting the year and the month from ticket_issued_date
    train_mod['year'] = train_mod['ticket_issued_date'].dt.year
    train_mod['month'] = train_mod['ticket_issued_date'].dt.month
    # Eliminating the ticket_issued_date variable
    del train_mod['ticket_issued_date']

    # Data Cleaning

    # Eliminating the entries in the train dataset containing data insertion mistakes
    # in the ticket_issued_date column
    train_cleaned = train_mod[(train_mod['year'] != 1938) & 
                              (train_mod['year'] != 1963) & 
                              (train_mod['year'] != 1988)]
    # Eliminating entries with null values in compliance
    train_cleaned = train_cleaned[pd.notnull(train_cleaned['compliance'])]

    # Filling the null values of lat and lon with the mean values in the column
    train_cleaned['lat'] = train_cleaned['lat'].fillna(train_cleaned['lat'].mean())
    train_cleaned['lon'] = train_cleaned['lon'].fillna(train_cleaned['lon'].mean())
    # Filling the null values of violator_cat with the most recurring value of the category
    train_cleaned['violator_cat'] = train_cleaned['violator_cat'].\
    fillna(train_cleaned['violator_cat'].value_counts().idxmax())

    # Converting the target value into integer type
    train_cleaned['compliance'] = train_cleaned['compliance'].astype('int')

    # Preparing train Data for Fitting Predicion Models

    # Selecting the variables to be used in the training data set
    train_selected = train_cleaned.loc[:,['ticket_id',
                                          'agency_name',
                                          'year',
                                          'month',
                                          'violator_cat',
                                          'lat',
                                          'lon',
                                          'disposition',
                                          'fine_amount',
                                          'late_fee',
                                          'discount',
                                          'compliance']]
    # Separating the features and the target variable in the train dataset
    train_features = train_selected.drop(columns='compliance')
    train_target = train_selected['compliance']
    # Adding category values to align it with the test dataset
    train_features['disposition'].cat.\
    add_categories(['Responsible (Fine Waived) by Admis',
                    'Responsible - Compl/Adj by Default',
                    'Responsible - Compl/Adj by Determi',
                    'Responsible by Dismissal'],
                    inplace=True)
    # Reordering the categories
    train_features['disposition'].cat.\
    reorder_categories(['Responsible (Fine Waived) by Admis',
                        'Responsible (Fine Waived) by Deter',
                        'Responsible - Compl/Adj by Default',
                        'Responsible - Compl/Adj by Determi',
                        'Responsible by Admission',
                        'Responsible by Default',
                        'Responsible by Determination',
                        'Responsible by Dismissal',
                        'Not responsible by City Dismissal',
                        'Not responsible by Determination',
                        'Not responsible by Dismissal',
                        'PENDING JUDGMENT',
                        'SET-ASIDE (PENDING JUDGMENT)'],
                        inplace=True)
    # Converting the categorical variables in train_features into indicator variables
    # to be used in Machine Learning
    train_feat_cat = pd.get_dummies(train_features)
    
    # Modifying the test data

    # Finding the occurrencies of each violator name
    viol_occ_t = test['violator_name'].value_counts()
    # Creating  a new variable containing the violator category
    # The used intervals are the same as thos eused for the train set
    violator_cat_s_t = pd.cut(viol_occ_t, bins=limits, labels=labels, 
                              right=True, include_lowest=False)
    # Renaming the series
    violator_cat_s_t.rename("violator_cat_s_t")
    # Converting the series into a dataframe and renaming the column
    violator_cat_d_t = violator_cat_s_t.to_frame().\
    rename(columns={"violator_name": "violator_cat"})

    # Merging the dataframe containing the violator categories with the test_coor dataset
    # by using violator_name as a index for train_coor (right join)
    test_mod = pd.merge(violator_cat_d_t, test_coord, how='right',
                        left_index=True, right_on='violator_name')

    # Converting the categorical variables into the correct datatype
    test_mod['agency_name'] = test_mod['agency_name'].astype('category')
    test_mod['disposition'] = test_mod['disposition'].astype('category')
    # Converting late_fee variable into categorical binary variables
    # (all cells of the column with value different from 0.0 are converted into value 'Fee',
    # all cells of the column with value 0.0 are converted into value 'No fee')
    # Then the type is changed into categorical
    test_mod.loc[test_mod['late_fee'] != 0.0, 'late_fee'] = 'Fee'
    test_mod.loc[test_mod['late_fee'] == 0.0, 'late_fee'] = 'No fee'
    test_mod['late_fee'] = test_mod['late_fee'].astype('category')
    # Creating a new categorical binary variable based on discount_amount variables
    # (all cells of the column with value different from 0.0 are converted into value 'Fee',
    # all cells of the column with value 0.0 are converted into value 'No fee')
    test_mod['discount'] = test_mod['discount_amount']
    test_mod.loc[test_mod['discount'] != 0.0, 'discount'] = 'Discount'
    test_mod.loc[test_mod['discount'] == 0.0, 'discount'] = 'No discount'
    test_mod['discount'] = test_mod['discount'].astype('category')
    # Converting the date related variable to datetime64   
    test_mod['ticket_issued_date'] = pd.to_datetime(test_mod['ticket_issued_date'])   
    # Extracting the year and the month from ticket_issued_date
    test_mod['year'] = test_mod['ticket_issued_date'].dt.year
    test_mod['month'] = test_mod['ticket_issued_date'].dt.month

    # Selecting the variables to be used in the test data set
    test_features = test_mod.loc[:,['ticket_id',
                                    'agency_name',
                                    'year',
                                    'month',
                                    'violator_cat',
                                    'lat',
                                    'lon',
                                    'disposition',
                                    'fine_amount',
                                    'late_fee',
                                    'discount']]

    # Filling the null values of lat and lon with the mean values in the column
    test_features['lat'] = test_features['lat'].fillna(test_features['lat'].mean())
    test_features['lon'] = test_features['lon'].fillna(test_features['lon'].mean())
    # Filling the null values of violator_cat with the most recurring value of the category
    test_features['violator_cat'] = test_features['violator_cat'].\
    fillna(test_features['violator_cat'].value_counts().idxmax())
    # Adding category values to align it with the train dataset
    test_features['agency_name'].cat.add_categories(['Health Department',
                                                     'Neighborhood City Halls'],
                                                      inplace=True)
    # Adding category values to align it with the train dataset
    test_features['disposition'].cat.add_categories(['Not responsible by City Dismissal',
                                                     'Not responsible by Determination',
                                                     'Not responsible by Dismissal',
                                                     'PENDING JUDGMENT',
                                                     'SET-ASIDE (PENDING JUDGMENT)'],
                                                      inplace=True)

    # Converting the categorical variables of test_features into indicator variables
    # to be used in Machine Learning
    test_feat_cat = pd.get_dummies(test_features)
    
    # Separating a validation data set and normalizing the features

    # Creating a validation data set by using the default 75% / 25% train-test split
    X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(train_feat_cat,
                                                      train_target,
                                                      random_state=0)
    
    # Model Fitting
    
    # Fitting a gradient boosted trees model with 1200 trees with a max depth of 5
    gb_1200 = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=1200,
                                         max_depth=5,
                                         min_samples_split=20,
                                         min_samples_leaf=10,
                                         learning_rate=0.0015,
                                         verbose=1,
                                         random_state=0).fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Making the predition
    
    X_test = test_feat_cat
    # Calculating the probability that the blight ticket will be paid on time
    # by using the test data
    y_test_prob = gb_1200.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]    
    # Storing the results of the prediction in a dataframe
    prediction = pd.DataFrame(index=test_feat_cat.index.tolist(),
                              columns=['ticket_id', 'compliance_probability'])
    prediction['ticket_id'] = test_feat_cat['ticket_id']
    prediction['compliance_probability'] = y_test_prob
    
    return prediction
